#  Day 32 – Identifying Stakeholders: Who Has a Stake in OpenMRS Security? | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Security Is Not Just a Technical Problem

One thing that has become clearer to me as this project has developed is that the hardest parts of GRC work are not the technical parts. Understanding FIPS 199 impact levels or configuring AWS GuardDuty are learnable skills. The harder challenge is the human side — getting the right people involved in security decisions, communicating risk in ways that resonate with different audiences, and making sure that the people who depend on a system have a meaningful voice in how it is secured.

That is what Task P-9 of the NIST RMF is about. Before moving into the formal Categorize step, the framework asks you to identify the key stakeholders — the individuals and groups who have an interest in the system, who are affected by its security posture, or whose decisions shape how the security program functions. Getting that picture right early in the process prevents the security program from being designed in a vacuum and then failing to gain adoption because the people who actually use the system were not involved.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task P-9 focuses on identifying stakeholders — both internal and external — who have an interest in the mission and business operations of the information system. The goal is not just to list names and titles. It is to understand what each stakeholder group cares about, what their relationship to the system's security is, what risks they introduce or help manage, and how they need to be engaged in the security program.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, I worked through stakeholder identification systematically — thinking about who interacts with the system, who is accountable for decisions about it, who bears the consequences if something goes wrong, and who has influence over the security posture even if they are not directly responsible for it.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clicked hardest today is that different stakeholders do not just have different roles — they have genuinely different and sometimes competing interests, and a security program that does not acknowledge those tensions will struggle to get implemented.

The clearest example for OpenMRS is the tension between clinicians and security administrators. Clinicians care about speed and access — they need to get to patient information quickly, without friction, in the middle of a busy clinical day. Security controls that add steps — MFA prompts, session timeouts, access request workflows — create friction that clinicians experience as obstacles to doing their jobs. That friction is not imaginary or unreasonable. In a clinical environment, an extra thirty seconds of authentication delay multiplied across dozens of patient encounters adds up to meaningful time that could be spent on care.

Security administrators care about access control, audit trails, and minimizing the risk of unauthorized access to ePHI. From their perspective, MFA and session timeouts are basic safeguards for a High-impact system handling sensitive patient data.

Both perspectives are legitimate. The security program that ignores the clinician perspective and implements controls purely from a security standpoint will face workarounds — shared passwords, propped-open sessions, shadow systems. The security program that ignores the security perspective and defers to clinician convenience will have real gaps.

The stakeholder mapping exercise is how you identify those tensions before they become implementation failures.

